RESULT: Control Output Cable (+) sits at approximately −12 V with respect to ground in all measurements, while Control Output Cable (−) is near 0 V. The measured voltages do not change between switch open and closed states, so the 12 V path behavior at the control-module output appears unchanged by the switch position in this test.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-21 01:28:31 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control-module indicator LED branch (red LED and its series resistor)'] hypothesis_explanation='From the tests we know:\n- The PSU output is correct and not polarity‑inverted: +12 V and 0 V are correctly wired to the control‑module input.\n- The same correct polarity appears at the control‑module output toward the load (−12 V on the conductor tied to PSU +, 0 V on the other), and this does not change with switch operation.\n- The load does not turn on, but the load module has a series diode that only conducts when polarity is correct. Since polarity is correct at the load, the diode would permit current if voltage were present across the lamp; the lamp staying off is therefore consistent with there being NO closed current path through the control module to the load.\n- Yet the red LED on the control module (the “inverted cables indicator”) is ON. By design, that LED is wired between the 12 V and 0 V lines with polarity such that it should light only if the module input polarity is reversed. In our case the polarity is NOT reversed, so for the LED to conduct now, its internal orientation or its series wiring must be wrong (effectively flipped) relative to the actual 12 V rail, or that branch is miswired so that it is across some unintended potentials.\n\nThus the consistent explanation is not a field wiring or cable‑swap problem but an internal fault in the control module: specifically the LED+resistor indicator branch is miswired or its LED is installed with reversed polarity. This fault makes the LED illuminate under correct wiring conditions (falsely indicating a swap) while the rest of the control circuit and switch path are otherwise not providing the correct series connection to the load, preventing the lamp from turning on.\n\nI therefore hypothesize an internal wiring/orientation fault in the control‑module indicator LED branch (the red LED and its series resistor). Repair would involve inspecting the control module internals and correcting the orientation/connections of that LED/resistor branch according to the schematic so it only sees forward bias when the module input polarity is actually inverted.'
