2026-04-21 01:29:16 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['orientation / polarity configuration of PSU output pair relative to control-module input pair', 'orientation / polarity configuration of control-module output pair relative to load-module input pair'] hypothesis_explanation='All individual components have tested good: the PSU provides 12 V, the control-module wiring and indicator branch are intact, and the inter‑module cables themselves are continuous. However, measurements show that at both the control-module output and the load-module input the conductor intended to be ‘+’ is sitting at about −12 V with respect to the chosen ground, and the conductor intended to be ‘−’ is near 0 V. The load-module protection diode then sees −12 V on its anode and 0 V on its cathode, so it is reverse‑biased and no current flows through either lamp. The red inverted‑cables indicator is lit, confirming that somewhere the + and − lines are reversed between modules.\n\nSince repairs to the control-module internal wiring and to the physical inter‑module cables themselves had no effect, the remaining plausible fault is a configuration/connection error: the fast‑connection terminals between modules are mated in the wrong orientation, effectively inverting the polarity between PSU and control module and/or between control module and load. Correcting the plug orientation (ensuring the PSU (+) line mates to the control-module (+) line, and the control-module (+) line to the load-module (+) line) should restore normal operation, turning off the red LED and allowing the diode to conduct and the lamps to light when the switch is closed.'
